{
  "response_text": "The data reveals consistent baseline behavior among non-learning E-RO households, with initial equitable distribution across households. The count remains stable at 20 in the first simulation run throughout all time steps. In other simulations, temporal fluctuations emerge: transient increases (up to 40 households) and decreases (down to 23 or fewer) occur but progressively resolve back to baseline values in most cases. Notably, these patterns align with the absence of learning behaviors (homog-behav-types?=True) and social-susceptibility (set to 0.0), suggesting external factors like risk-averse herd management decisions and pasture stress combinations drive these oscillations despite the lack of adaptive strategies. The recurring stabilization to baseline values (20) across nearly all runs reflects equilibrium in non-learning systems under fixed policy conditions, though short-term variability across simulations indicates sensitivity to stochastic climate inputs (rainfall variability). Such dynamics could inform evaluations of behavioral type resilience and system stability under stochastic environmental pressures."










































































































































}

